DATA.Name: results
DATA.Value.name: Geothermal energy

DATA.Name: results
DATA.Value.name: Grid mix
DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity of grid mix as reported. The values take electrical and thermal kWh supply into account. Cross-border power exchanges are not included. The publication covers only direct emissions from power plants. Provided by the IEA in 2013. Published by ADEME. NOTE: this value is provided in CO2 only and does not include the impact of other GHGs. This factor will be deprecated.

DATA.Name: results

DATA.Name: results
DATA.Value.name: Electricity generation â WTT
DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity of WTT Electricity generation Africa (average). Well-to-Tank (WTT) conversion factors for UK and overseas electricity should be used to report the Scope 3 emissions of extraction and refining and transportation of primary fuels before their use in the generation of electricity. It should be noted that electricity generation and transmission and distribution losses have separate WTT emissions assigned to them. Retrieved from the Conversion Factors 2021: flat file published by the UK BEIS/Defra at the source URL.

Retrieved from the Conversion Factors 2021: flat file published by the UK BEIS/Defra at the source URL.

DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity of grid mix as reported (areas covered by the Hong Kong Electric Company). Available in  HK Electric Investments Sustainability Report 2020. It is combined generation and T&D factor.

DATA.Name: results
DATA.Value.name: Grid mix
DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity of grid mix as reported. The values take electrical and thermal kWh supply into account. Cross-border power exchanges are not included. The publication covers only direct emissions from power plants. Provided by the IEA in 2013. Published by ADEME. NOTE: this value is provided in CO2 only and does not include the impact of other GHGs. This factor will be deprecated.

DATA.Name: results
DATA.Value.name: Electricity generation â WTT
DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity of WTT Electricity generation Croatia. Well-to-Tank (WTT) conversion factors for UK and overseas electricity should be used to report the Scope 3 emissions of extraction and refining and transportation of primary fuels before their use in the generation of electricity. It should be noted that electricity generation and transmission and distribution losses have separate WTT emissions assigned to them. Retrieved from the Conversion Factors 2021: flat file published by the UK BEIS/Defra at the source URL.

DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity of WTT Electricity generation South Africa. Well-to-Tank (WTT) conversion factors for UK and overseas electricity should be used to report the Scope 3 emissions of extraction and refining and transportation of primary fuels before their use in the generation of electricity. It should be noted that electricity generation and transmission and distribution losses have separate WTT emissions assigned to them. Retrieved from the Conversion Factors 2021: flat file published by the UK BEIS/Defra at the source URL.

DATA.Name: results
DATA.Value.name: Commuter rail passenger train
DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity for commuter rail passenger train with no information on inclusion of upstream emissions. This emission factor accounts for commuter rail services between a central city and adjacent suburbs (also called regional rail or suburban rail). It is intended for use in the distance-based method defined in the GHG Protocol Scope 3 Calculation Guidance. If fuel data are available then the fuel-based method should be used. Available in the EPA's GHG Emission Factors Hub (xlsx).

DATA.Name: results
DATA.Value.name: National rail passenger train
DATA.Value.description: Emission intensity for UK national rail passenger train including fuel consumption. The national rail factor refers to an average emission per passenger kilometre for diesel and electric trains in 2019-20. The factor is sourced from information from the Office of the Rail Regulatorâs National rail trends for 2019-20 (ORR 2020). This has been calculated based on total electricity and diesel consumed by the railway for the year sourced from the Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC) and the total number of passenger kilometres (from National Rail Trends). Retrieved from the Conversion Factors 2021: flat file published by the UK BEIS/Defra at the source URL.
